class Solution:
    def twoSum(self, nums: List[int], target: int) -> List[int]:
        dic = {}
        for i,num in enumerate(nums):
            complement = target - num
            if complement in dic:
                return [dic[complement],i]
            dic[num] = i

Real life Implementation: 
While processing data one item at a time, quickly check if a previously seen item can combine with the current item to satisfy a condition.
 1. Banking & Fraud Detection

Suppose a bank wants to detect whether two transactions together equal a suspicious amount.

Example
Transactions:
₹300
₹700
₹150
₹500

Suspicious amount = ₹1000

As each transaction arrives:

300 → store
700 → 1000 - 700 = 300 ✓ Found!

The bank immediately knows:

300 + 700 = 1000

No need to compare with every previous transaction.    


2. E-commerce Discounts

Imagine Amazon has coupons:

Coupon A = $40
Coupon B = $60
Coupon C = $30

Customer wants exactly:

$100 discount

Instead of checking every pair:

40 + 60 ✓
40 + 30 ✗
60 + 30 ✗

Use a dictionary to instantly find the required partner coupon.

3. Music Playlist

Suppose Spotify wants two songs whose durations equal a target.

Songs:
180 sec
240 sec
120 sec
60 sec

Target = 300 sec

While scanning:

180 → store
240 → need 60
